title: Turning Point halftime show labelled ‘patriotic’
description: Former White House press secretary Sean Spicer says the Turning Point halftime show was “patriotic”.   “They expect potentially 20-30 million people who have watched it when the final tallies come in,” Mr Spicer told Sky News host James Macpherson.  “The Turning Point wasn’t about promoting one side or another; it was patriotic.”

title: ‘Battle raging inside the Liberal Party’ to become more central
description: Liberal MP Tony Pasin believes One Nation has shown Liberals that they don’t need to move further toward the centre.   “The battle that’s raging inside the Liberal Party now over the course of the last five years, I think, has been resolved by the uptake in primary vote in One Nation,” Mr Pasin told Sky News host Danica De Giorgo.  “For too long, this idea that we need to lurch to the left was gaining some currency.   “If some of my colleagues are scared of the phrase mass migration, they need to get out more.”

title: Albanese ‘playing catch up’ to Minns government protest crackdown
description: Nationals Senator Matt Canavan says Prime Minister Anthony Albanese is “playing catch-up” to New South Wales Premier Chris Minns’ actions against the anti-Israel and pro-Palestine protesters.  “We had to take action, I am glad … an Australian government has taken action,” Mr Canavan said.  “Like always … the prime minister is playing catch up here.”

title: ‘It’s insane’: Absurd protesters are ‘exploiting democracy’ and draining resources
description: The Daily Telegraph’s Tim Blair criticises protesters for wasting police resources.  “We see the West’s generosity, its philosophical generosity, we open the door, we allow marches, we allow protests and that gets exploited.  “We have a protest against the protest being protested.  “It’s insane.  “It’s certainly an exploited area of democracy.”

title: ‘Bring the temperature down’: Sydney is ‘pretty scary’ as police and protesters clash
description: Former Labor councillor Linda Scott says the streets of Sydney have been “pretty scary” amid Israeli President Isaac Herzog’s visit to Australia and the subsequent clashing between protesters and police.   “I'm a pretty simple person … two wrongs don’t make a right … it’s so important that Australians have the right to protest," Ms Scott told Sky News host Paul Murray.  “I do think it is important to bring the temperature down.”

title: ‘What were they doing?’: Expert breaks down Sydney pro-Palestinian protests
description: Former Australian Jewish association president David Adler reminisces on how pro-Palestinian protesters were celebrating Hamas’ attack on Israel at the Opera House in 2023.   This comes amid Israeli President Isaac Herzog’s visit to Australia.  “That displays the lie that this is a reaction to what Israel has done in Gaza,” Mr Adler told Sky News host Danica De Giorgio.  “On the 9th of October 2023, when those Opera House events occurred, Israel had done nothing … what were they doing? … it was more a celebration of the attack that Hamas was successful in against Israel.”

title: Radical activists put on ‘disgraceful display’ amid Isaac Herzog visit
description: Former Australian Jewish association president David Adler details the “disgraceful” display of protesting that occurred during the visit of Israeli President Isaac Herzog.   “It was a disgraceful display, we’re supposed to have a system of law and order in this country,” Mr Adler told Sky News host Danica De Giorgio.  “The radical activists ignored the court order, and they left the police with an impossible situation.”

title: ‘Reform now ahead of Labour’: Starmer’s popularity in Scotland plummets
description: Reform UK Leader Nigel Farage believes either UK Prime Minister Keir Starmer or First Minister of Scotland John Swinney has to go for Labour to stand a chance in Scotland.   “This new upstart party called Reform has come along and is now ahead of Labour in the polls,” Mr Farage told Sky News host Paul Murray.   “Starmer is even more unpopular in Scotland than he is in England.  “How on earth can Labour fight the Scottish parliament elections.  “One of them has got to go.”

title: ‘Can’t last long’: Farage blasts ‘most unpopular PM in UK history’ Keir Starmer
description: Reform UK Leader Nigel Farage slams UK Prime Minister Keir Starmer after further scrutiny of Mandelson’s appointment.   “The most unpopular prime minister in the history of our country,” Mr Farage told Sky News host Paul Murray.  “He’s got no credibility within his party.  “The bloke is a complete disaster.  “He can’t last long.”

title: ‘Wipeout on May 7’: Farage confident after Labour slammed in the polls
description: Reform UK Leader Nigel Farage believes Reform UK stand a good chance at the upcoming elections on May 7.   “If we could become the official Opposition in Scotland that would be the most incredible result,” Mr Farage told Sky News host Paul Murray.  “Things look good.  “It’s wipeout on May the seventh, whatever happens.”

title: Jewish Council of Australia’s ‘desperation for relevance’ on full display amid anti-Herzog ad
description: Sky News host Freya Leach details how the Jewish Council of Australia’s “desperation for relevance” was on full display after an anti-Herzog advertisement falsified the signatures of Jewish community members.   “Speaking of left-wing groups, the Jewish Council of Australia, which is a fringe, left-wing supposedly Jewish representative group although they represent a tiny, tiny, tiny fraction of the Jewish community,” Ms Leach said.  “Frankly, their desperation for relevance was on full display … when they took out a massive full-page ad in The Age and the Sydney Morning Herald, they claimed their open letter against Herzog’s visit was signed by 1000 Jews.”

title: ‘Absurd’: Bad Bunny’s Super Bowl halftime show ranked sixth best by New York Times
description: Sky News host Rita Panahi reacts to fans at the Super Bowl halftime show who were “not feeling the vibe” of Bad Bunny.  “Bad Bunny’s controversial halftime Super Bowl show has been ranked as the sixth best by the New York Times, coming in behind Prince at number one,” Ms Panahi said.   “The fans in the stadium seem rather underwhelmed.”

title: Grace Tame under fire over ‘widely condemned’ comment against Jews
description: Sky News host Freya Leach criticises Grace Tame over her ‘globalise the intifada’ chant at yesterday’s pro-Palestine protest in Town Hall, Sydney.   “Grace Tame, she popped up at the protest yesterday evening at Town Hall and chanted ‘globalise the intifada’,” Ms Leach said.  “Now that’s a chant that has been widely condemned, it’s widely acknowledged that it’s calling for the globalising of violence against Jews.”

title: ‘Biggest virtue signal fest’: Bad Bunny’s Super Bowl performance labelled ‘worst’ in history
description: Comedian Alex Stein calls Bad Bunny’s Super Bowl halftime show the “biggest virtue signal fest”.   “My least favourite part were the two guys gyrating together next to the pickup truck, I don’t understand why that was necessary,” Mr Stein told Sky News host Rita Panahi.   “It was the worst halftime Super Bowl show I’ve ever seen, and it didn’t appeal to anybody.”

title: ‘Rewriting of history’: Klugman claims global Islamist terrorism was always a threat
description: Strategic Analysis Australia Director Michael Shoebridge calls out the Office of National Intelligence for claiming global Islamist terrorism was always on the list of threats to Australia.   “On that list there was not global Islamist terrorism as a threat to Australia,” Mr Shoebridge told Sky News host Danica De Giorgio.  “Now we’re told by his replacement that global Islamist terrorism remains at the top of the list.  “This does look like a little bit like a polite rewriting of history”
